article.headline: Nolan, Cash lead Detroit comeback
article.linkText: Shock muster rally from 23 down to top Fever
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana Fever scored the most first-half points in their five-year team history to build a 19-point halftime lead over the WNBA champion Detroit Shock. It wasn't enough. Detroit held the Fever without a field goal over the game's final 9:49 en route to an 83-79 victory Wednesday night.
WNBA's largest comebacks
23 -- 6/09/04 Detroit at Indiana
22 -- 8/20/99 Utah at Phoenix
22 -- 6/26/03 LA at San Antonio
20 -- 8/21/03 New York at Washington
19 -- 7/01/01 Indiana vs. Phoenix
19 -- 8/17/03 Detroit at Seattle
19 -- 6/22/99 Phoenix at Washington
Deanna Nolan scored a career-high 29 points and the Shock came back from a 23-point deficit, the largest ever overcome in a WNBA game. Detroit trailed 41-18 late in the first half. "We knew we could come back," said Nolan, 8-of-14 from the field, 3-of-5 from 3-point range and 10-of-11 from the free-throw line. "We knew we could play much harder than we did in the first half." Swin Cash scored 21 points and Ruth Riley 12 for the Shock (3-3). Kelly Miller scored 20 points for the Fever (3-3). The Shock held two-time All-Star Tamika Catchings to 15 points. She had just two free throws in the second half. Detroit shot 59 percent (19-of-32) in the second half. "I think our difference was the zone," Nolan said. "We were getting to their shooters and contesting shots." The Shock outscored the Fever 12-2 over the first 3:20 after the break. Indiana coach Brian Winters said that made a difference. "I knew they would try to come back against us," Winters said. "We said the first three to five minutes of the second half were important. We needed to control that time, and we did not. "They came out and pressed us, and we panicked a little bit. They scored 12 points on turnovers in the second half. That's how teams come back." Coretta Brown hit a layup to give the Fever a 68-55 lead with 9:48 to play, but that was Indiana's last basket. The Shock went on a 24-7 run and took their first lead since scoring the game's first basket. Deanna Jackson hit two free throws to cut Detroit's lead to 79-77 with 19.3 seconds remaining, but Nolan made four free throws to keep her team ahead. "They're going to give me gray hairs," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said of his players. "Indiana played spectacular in the first half. Their energy level was good and ours was zero." Kate Starbird scored five points and Catchings four as the Fever went on a 23-6 run over an eight-minute span of the first half, improving their lead from 18-12 to 41-18 with 4:41 to go. "In the second half, we full-court pressed. That hurt them. We played zone, took away their mid-range shots and forced them to take 3s," Laimbeer said. Catchings, hampered by fouls, played just 14 minutes in the second half. The Fever, who hit 6-of-9 3-pointers in the first half, made 2-of-9 in the second half.
